[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] This involves matrix products and explicit inversion, thus limiting the practical block size.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] A task that often arises in practice is that one needs to update a Cholesky decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] The question is now whether one can use the Cholesky decomposition of ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} }$ that was computed before to compute the Cholesky decomposition of ${\textstyle {\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] The specific case, where the updated matrix ${\textstyle {\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}}$ is related to the matrix ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} }$ by ${\textstyle {\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}=\mathbf {A} +c\,\mathbf {x} \mathbf {x} ^{*}}$ , is known as a *rank-one update*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] Here the constant c is allowed to be negative, but must always be such that the new matrix ${\textstyle {\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}}$ is still positive definite.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] A *rank-n update* is one where for a matrix ${\textstyle \mathbf {M} }$ one updates the decomposition such that ${\textstyle {\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}=\mathbf {A} +\mathbf {M} \mathbf {M} ^{*}}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] This can be achieved by successively performing rank-one updates for each of the columns of ${\textstyle \mathbf {M} }$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] These formulas may be used to determine the Cholesky factor after the insertion of rows or columns in any position, if the row and column dimensions are appropriately set (including to zero).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] The above algorithms show that every positive definite matrix ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} }$ has a Cholesky decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] This result can be extended to the positive semi-definite case by a limiting argument.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] The argument is not fully constructive, i.e., it gives no explicit numerical algorithms for computing Cholesky factors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] If ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} }$ is an ${\textstyle n\times n}$ positive semi-definite matrix, then the sequence ${\textstyle \left(\mathbf {A} _{k}\right)_{k}:=\left(\mathbf {A} +{\frac {1}{k}}\mathbf {I} _{n}\right)_{k}}$ consists of positive definite matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] (This is an immediate consequence of, for example, the spectral mapping theorem for the polynomial functional calculus.) Also, $\mathbf {A} _{k}\rightarrow \mathbf {A} \quad {\text{for}}\quad k\rightarrow \infty$ in operator norm.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] From the positive definite case, each ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} _{k}}$ has Cholesky decomposition ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} _{k}=\mathbf {L} _{k}\mathbf {L} _{k}^{*}}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] The ${\textstyle \leq }$ holds because ${\textstyle M_{n}(\mathbb {C} )}$ equipped with the operator norm is a C* algebra.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] So ${\textstyle \left(\mathbf {L} _{k}\right)_{k}}$ is a bounded set in the Banach space of operators, therefore relatively compact (because the underlying vector space is finite-dimensional).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] Consequently, it has a convergent subsequence, also denoted by ${\textstyle \left(\mathbf {L} _{k}\right)_{k}}$ , with limit ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} }$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] Because the underlying vector space is finite-dimensional, all topologies on the space of operators are equivalent.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] So ${\textstyle \left(\mathbf {L} _{k}\right)_{k}}$ tends to ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} }$ in norm means ${\textstyle \left(\mathbf {L} _{k}\right)_{k}}$ tends to ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} }$ entrywise.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] This in turn implies that, since each ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} _{k}}$ is lower triangular with non-negative diagonal entries, ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} }$ is also.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] Let ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} }$ be a positive semi-definite Hermitian matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] Then it can be written as a product of its square root matrix, ${\textstyle \mathbf {A} =\mathbf {B} \mathbf {B} ^{*}}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] Now QR decomposition can be applied to ${\textstyle \mathbf {B} ^{*}}$ , resulting in ${\textstyle \mathbf {B} ^{*}=\mathbf {Q} \mathbf {R} }$ , where ${\textstyle \mathbf {Q} }$ is unitary and ${\textstyle \mathbf {R} }$ is upper triangular.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] Inserting the decomposition into the original equality yields ${\textstyle A=\mathbf {B} \mathbf {B} ^{*}=(\mathbf {QR} )^{*}\mathbf {QR} =\mathbf {R} ^{*}\mathbf {Q} ^{*}\mathbf {QR} =\mathbf {R} ^{*}\mathbf {R} }$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] Setting ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} =\mathbf {R} ^{*}}$ completes the proof.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] The Cholesky factorization can be generalized to (not necessarily finite) matrices with operator entries.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] Let ${\textstyle \{{\mathcal {H}}_{n}\}}$ be a sequence of Hilbert spaces.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] there is ${\textstyle \langle h,\mathbf {A} h\rangle \geq 0}$ , then there exists a lower triangular operator matrix **L** such that **A** = **LL***.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/cholesky-decomposition] One can also take the diagonal entries of **L** to be positive.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In mathematics, the **conjugate gradient method** is an algorithm for the numerical solution of particular systems of linear equations, namely those whose matrix is positive-semidefinite.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method is often implemented as an iterative algorithm, applicable to sparse systems that are too large to be handled by a direct implementation or other direct methods such as the Cholesky decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Large sparse systems often arise when numerically solving partial differential equations or optimization problems.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can also be used to solve unconstrained optimization problems such as energy minimization.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] It is commonly attributed to Magnus Hestenes and Eduard Stiefel, who programmed it on the Z4, and extensively researched it.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The biconjugate gradient method provides a generalization to non-symmetric matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Various nonlinear conjugate gradient methods seek minima of nonlinear optimization problems.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] We denote the unique solution of this system by $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can be derived from several different perspectives, including specialization of the conjugate direction method for optimization, and variation of the Arnoldi/Lanczos iteration for eigenvalue problems.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Despite differences in their approaches, these derivations share a common topic—proving the orthogonality of the residuals and conjugacy of the search directions.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] These two properties are crucial to developing the well-known succinct formulation of the method.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Two vectors are conjugate if and only if they are orthogonal with respect to this inner product.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Being conjugate is a symmetric relation: if $\mathbf {u}$ is conjugate to $\mathbf {v}$ , then $\mathbf {v}$ is conjugate to $\mathbf {u}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] is a set of n mutually conjugate vectors with respect to $\mathbf {A}$ , i.e. $\mathbf {p} _{i}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {A} \mathbf {p} _{j}=0$ for all $i\neq j$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This gives the following method for solving the equation $\mathbf {Ax} =\mathbf {b}$ : find a sequence of n conjugate directions, and then compute the coefficients $\alpha _{k}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If we choose the conjugate vectors $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ carefully, then we may not need all of them to obtain a good approximation to the solution $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] So, we want to regard the conjugate gradient method as an iterative method.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This also allows us to approximately solve systems where n is so large that the direct method would take too much time.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] We denote the initial guess for $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ by $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ (we can assume without loss of generality that $\mathbf {x} _{0}=\mathbf {0}$ , otherwise consider the system $\mathbf {Az} =\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{0}$ instead).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Starting with $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ we search for the solution and in each iteration we need a metric to tell us whether we are closer to the solution $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ (that is unknown to us).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This suggests taking the first basis vector $\mathbf {p} _{0}$ to be the negative of the gradient of f at $\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {x} _{0}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The gradient of f equals $\mathbf {Ax} -\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Starting with an initial guess $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ , this means we take $\mathbf {p} _{0}=\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{0}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The other vectors in the basis will be conjugate to the gradient, hence the name *conjugate gradient method*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Note that $\mathbf {p} _{0}$ is also the residual provided by this initial step of the algorithm.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] As observed above, $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ is the negative gradient of f at $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ , so the gradient descent method would require to move in the direction **r***k*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Here, however, we insist that the directions $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ must be conjugate to each other.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] A practical way to enforce this is by requiring that the next search direction be built out of the current residual and all previous search directions.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugation constraint is an orthonormal-type constraint and hence the algorithm can be viewed as an example of Gram-Schmidt orthonormalization.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] (see the picture at the top of the article for the effect of the conjugacy constraint on convergence).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] where the last equality follows from the definition of $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The above algorithm gives the most straightforward explanation of the conjugate gradient method.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Seemingly, the algorithm as stated requires storage of all previous searching directions and residue vectors, as well as many matrix–vector multiplications, and thus can be computationally expensive.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] However, a closer analysis of the algorithm shows that $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf {r} _{j}$ , i.e. $\mathbf {r} _{i}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {r} _{j}=0$ , for $i\neq j$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Therefore, $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ can be regarded as the projection of $\mathbf {x}$ on the Krylov subspace.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The algorithm is detailed below for solving $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ where $\mathbf {A}$ is a real, symmetric, positive-definite matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The input vector $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ can be an approximate initial solution or $\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] It is a different formulation of the exact procedure described above.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This is the most commonly used algorithm.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The same formula for $\beta _{k}$ is also used in the Fletcher–Reeves nonlinear conjugate gradient method.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] We note that $\mathbf {x} _{1}$ is computed by the gradient descent method applied to $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Setting $\beta _{k}=0$ would similarly make $\mathbf {x} _{k+1}$ computed by the gradient descent method from $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ , i.e., can be used as a simple implementation of a restart of the conjugate gradient iterations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Restarts could slow down convergence, but may improve stability if the conjugate gradient method misbehaves, e.g., due to round-off error.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The former is used in the algorithm to avoid an extra multiplication by $\mathbf {A}$ since the vector $\mathbf {Ap} _{k}$ is already computed to evaluate $\alpha _{k}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The latter may be more accurate, substituting the explicit calculation $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}:=\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{k+1}$ for the implicit one by the recursion subject to round-off error accumulation, and is thus recommended for an occasional evaluation.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] A norm of the residual is typically used for stopping criteria.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The norm of the explicit residual $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}:=\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{k+1}$ provides a guaranteed level of accuracy both in exact arithmetic and in the presence of the rounding errors, where convergence naturally stagnates.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In contrast, the implicit residual $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}:=\mathbf {r} _{k}-\alpha _{k}\mathbf {Ap} _{k}$ is known to keep getting smaller in amplitude well below the level of rounding errors and thus cannot be used to determine the stagnation of convergence.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In the algorithm, $\alpha _{k}$ is chosen such that $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The $\beta _{k}$ is chosen such that $\mathbf {p} _{k+1}$ is conjugate to $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] because $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}$ and $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ are orthogonal by design.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] using that the search directions $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ are conjugated and again that the residuals are orthogonal.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This gives the $\beta$ in the algorithm after cancelling $\alpha _{k}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] in order to find an approximate solution to the system.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Our first step is to calculate the residual vector **r**0 associated with **x**0.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Since this is the first iteration, we will use the residual vector **r**0 as our initial search direction **p**0; the method of selecting **p***k* will change in further iterations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This result completes the first iteration, the result being an "improved" approximate solution to the system, **x**1.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Our next step in the process is to compute the scalar *β*0 that will eventually be used to determine the next search direction **p**1.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] We now compute the scalar *α*1 using our newly acquired **p**1 using the same method as that used for *α*0.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Finally, we find **x**2 using the same method as that used to find **x**1.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The result, **x**2, is a "better" approximation to the system's solution than **x**1 and **x**0.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If exact arithmetic were to be used in this example instead of limited-precision, then the exact solution would theoretically have been reached after *n* = 2 iterations (*n* being the order of the system).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Under exact arithmetic, the number of iterations required is no more than the order of the matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This behavior is known as the **finite termination property** of the conjugate gradient method.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] It refers to the method's ability to reach the exact solution of a linear system in a finite number of steps—at most equal to the dimension of the system—when exact arithmetic is used.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This property arises from the fact that, at each iteration, the method generates a residual vector that is orthogonal to all previous residuals.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] These residuals form a mutually orthogonal set.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In an *n*-dimensional space, it is impossible to construct more than *n* linearly independent and mutually orthogonal vectors unless one of them is the zero vector.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Therefore, once a zero residual appears, the method has reached the solution and must terminate.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This ensures that the conjugate gradient method converges in at most *n* steps.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] We start from an initial guess $\mathbf {x} _{0}={\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Since A is symmetric positive-definite and the system is 2-dimensional, the conjugate gradient method should find the exact solution in no more than 2 steps.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The output confirms that the method reaches ${\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\end{bmatrix}}$ after two iterations, consistent with the theoretical prediction.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This example illustrates how the conjugate gradient method behaves as a direct method under idealized conditions.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The finite termination property also has practical implications in solving large sparse systems, which frequently arise in scientific and engineering applications.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] For instance, discretizing the two-dimensional Laplace equation $\nabla ^{2}u=0$ using finite differences on a uniform grid leads to a sparse linear system $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ , where A is symmetric and positive definite.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Using a $5\times 5$ interior grid yields a $25\times 25$ system, and the coefficient matrix A has a five-point stencil pattern.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Each row of A contains at most five nonzero entries corresponding to the central point and its immediate neighbors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Although the system dimension is 25, the conjugate gradient method is theoretically guaranteed to terminate in at most 25 iterations under exact arithmetic.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In practice, convergence often occurs in far fewer steps due to the matrix's spectral properties.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This efficiency makes CGM particularly attractive for solving large-scale systems arising from partial differential equations, such as those found in heat conduction, fluid dynamics, and electrostatics.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can theoretically be viewed as a direct method, as in the absence of round-off error it produces the exact solution after a finite number of iterations, which is not larger than the size of the matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In practice, the exact solution is never obtained since the conjugate gradient method is unstable with respect to even small perturbations, e.g., most directions are not in practice conjugate, due to a degenerative nature of generating the Krylov subspaces.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] As an iterative method, the conjugate gradient method monotonically (in the energy norm) improves approximations $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ to the exact solution and may reach the required tolerance after a relatively small (compared to the problem size) number of iterations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The improvement is typically linear and its speed is determined by the condition number $\kappa (A)$ of the system matrix A : the larger $\kappa (A)$ is, the slower the improvement.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] However, an interesting case appears when the eigenvalues are spaced logarithmically for a large symmetric matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] For example, let $A=QDQ^{T}$ where Q is a random orthogonal matrix and D is a diagonal matrix with eigenvalues ranging from $\lambda _{n}=1$ to $\lambda _{1}=10^{6}$ , spaced logarithmically.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Despite the finite termination property of CGM, where the exact solution should theoretically be reached in at most n steps, the method may exhibit stagnation in convergence.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In such a scenario, even after many more iterations—e.g., ten times the matrix size—the error may only decrease modestly (e.g., to $10^{-5}$ ).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Moreover, the iterative error may oscillate significantly, making it unreliable as a stopping condition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This poor convergence is not explained by the condition number alone (e.g., $\kappa _{2}(A)=10^{6}$ ), but rather by the eigenvalue distribution itself.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] When the eigenvalues are more evenly spaced or randomly distributed, such convergence issues are typically absent, highlighting that CGM performance depends not only on $\kappa (A)$ but also on how the eigenvalues are distributed.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If $\kappa (A)$ is large, preconditioning is commonly used to replace the original system $\mathbf {Ax} -\mathbf {b} =0$ with $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}(\mathbf {Ax} -\mathbf {b} )=0$ such that $\kappa (\mathbf {M} ^{-1}\mathbf {A} )$ is smaller than $\kappa (\mathbf {A} )$ , see below.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] where $\Pi _{k}$ is the set of polynomials of maximal degree k .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Let $\left(\mathbf {x} _{k}\right)_{k}$ be the iterative approximations of the exact solution $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ , and define the errors as $\mathbf {e} _{k}:=\mathbf {x} _{k}-\mathbf {x} _{*}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] where $\sigma (\mathbf {A} )$ denotes the spectrum, and $\kappa (\mathbf {A} )$ denotes the condition number.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This shows $k={\tfrac {1}{2}}{\sqrt {\kappa (\mathbf {A} )}}\log \left(\left\|\mathbf {e} _{0}\right\|_{\mathbf {A} }\varepsilon ^{-1}\right)$ iterations suffices to reduce the error to $2\varepsilon$ for any $\varepsilon >0$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This limit shows a faster convergence rate compared to the iterative methods of Jacobi or Gauss–Seidel which scale as $\approx 1-{\frac {2}{\kappa (\mathbf {A} )}}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] No round-off error is assumed in the convergence theorem, but the convergence bound is commonly valid in practice as theoretically explained by Anne Greenbaum.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If initialized randomly, the first stage of iterations is often the fastest, as the error is eliminated within the Krylov subspace that initially reflects a smaller effective condition number.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The second stage of convergence is typically well defined by the theoretical convergence bound with ${\textstyle {\sqrt {\kappa (\mathbf {A} )}}}$ , but may be super-linear, depending on a distribution of the spectrum of the matrix A and the spectral distribution of the error.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In the last stage, the smallest attainable accuracy is reached and the convergence stalls or the method may even start diverging.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In typical scientific computing applications in double-precision floating-point format for matrices of large sizes, the conjugate gradient method uses a stopping criterion with a tolerance that terminates the iterations during the first or second stage.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In most cases, preconditioning is necessary to ensure fast convergence of the conjugate gradient method.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}$ is symmetric positive-definite and $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}\mathbf {A}$ has a better condition number than $\mathbf {A} ,$ a preconditioned conjugate gradient method can be used.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The Cholesky decomposition of the preconditioner must be used to keep the symmetry (and positive definiteness) of the system.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] However, this decomposition does not need to be computed, and it is sufficient to know $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The preconditioner matrix $\mathbf {M}$ has to be symmetric positive-definite and fixed, i.e., cannot change from iteration to iteration.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If any of these assumptions on the preconditioner is violated, the behavior of the preconditioned conjugate gradient method may become unpredictable.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] An example of a commonly used preconditioner is the incomplete Cholesky factorization.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] It is important to keep in mind that we don't want to invert the matrix $\mathbf {M}$ explicitly in order to get $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}$ for use in the process, since inverting $\mathbf {M}$ would take more time/computational resources than solving the conjugate gradient algorithm itself.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] As an example, let's say that we are using a preconditioner coming from incomplete Cholesky factorization.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Since $\mathbf {r}$ and $\mathbf {L}$ and known, and $\mathbf {L}$ is lower triangular, solving for $\mathbf {a}$ is easy and computationally cheap by using forward substitution.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Since $\mathbf {a}$ and $\mathbf {L} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ are known, and $\mathbf {L} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ is upper triangular, solving for $\mathbf {z}$ is easy and computationally cheap by using backward substitution.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Using this method, there is no need to invert $\mathbf {M}$ or $\mathbf {L}$ explicitly at all, and we still obtain $\mathbf {z}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In numerically challenging applications, sophisticated preconditioners are used, which may lead to variable preconditioning, changing between iterations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Even if the preconditioner is symmetric positive-definite on every iteration, the fact that it may change makes the arguments above invalid, and in practical tests leads to a significant slow down of the convergence of the algorithm presented above.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] may dramatically improve the convergence in this case.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This version of the preconditioned conjugate gradient method can be called **flexible**, as it allows for variable preconditioning.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The flexible version is also shown to be robust even if the preconditioner is not symmetric positive definite (SPD).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The implementation of the flexible version requires storing an extra vector.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] For a fixed SPD preconditioner, $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {z} _{k}=0,$ so both formulas for βk are equivalent in exact arithmetic, i.e., without the round-off error.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The mathematical explanation of the better convergence behavior of the method with the Polak–Ribière formula is that the method is **locally optimal** in this case, in particular, it does not converge slower than the locally optimal steepest descent method.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In both the original and the preconditioned conjugate gradient methods one only needs to set $\beta _{k}:=0$ in order to make them locally optimal, using the line search, steepest descent methods.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] With this substitution, vectors **p** are always the same as vectors **z**, so there is no need to store vectors **p**.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Thus, every iteration of these steepest descent methods is a bit cheaper compared to that for the conjugate gradient methods.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] However, the latter converge faster, unless a (highly) variable and/or non-SPD preconditioner is used, see above.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can also be derived using optimal control theory.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In this approach, the conjugate gradient method falls out as an optimal feedback controller, $u=k(x,v):=-\gamma _{a}\nabla f(x)-\gamma _{b}v$ for the double integrator system, ${\dot {x}}=v,\quad {\dot {v}}=u$ The quantities $\gamma _{a}$ and $\gamma _{b}$ are variable feedback gains.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can be applied to an arbitrary *n*-by-*m* matrix by applying it to normal equations **A**T**A** and right-hand side vector **A**T**b**, since **A**T**A** is a symmetric positive-semidefinite matrix for any **A**.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The result is **conjugate gradient on the normal equations** (**CGN** or **CGNR**).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] As an iterative method, it is not necessary to form **A**T**A** explicitly in memory but only to perform the matrix–vector and transpose matrix–vector multiplications.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Therefore, CGNR is particularly useful when *A* is a sparse matrix since these operations are usually extremely efficient.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] However the downside of forming the normal equations is that the condition number κ(**A**T**A**) is equal to κ2(**A**) and so the rate of convergence of CGNR may be slow and the quality of the approximate solution may be sensitive to roundoff errors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Finding a good preconditioner is often an important part of using the CGNR method.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Several algorithms have been proposed (e.g., CGLS, LSQR).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The LSQR algorithm purportedly has the best numerical stability when **A** is ill-conditioned, i.e., **A** has a large condition number.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The trivial modification is simply substituting the conjugate transpose for the real transpose everywhere.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The advantages and disadvantages of the conjugate gradient methods are summarized in the lecture notes by Nemirovsky and BenTal.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Solving it by conjugate gradient descent gives us rather bad convergence: $\|b-Wx_{k}\|^{2}=(1/t)^{k},\quad \|b-Wx_{n}\|^{2}=0$ In words, during the CG process, the error grows exponentially, until it suddenly becomes zero as the unique solution is found.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/krylov-subspace] The concept is named after Russian applied mathematician and naval engineer Alexei Krylov, who published a paper about the concept in 1931.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/krylov-subspace] Krylov subspaces are used in algorithms for finding approximate solutions to high-dimensional linear algebra problems.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/krylov-subspace] Many linear dynamical system tests in control theory, especially those related to controllability and observability, involve checking the rank of the Krylov subspace.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/krylov-subspace] These tests are equivalent to finding the span of the Gramians associated with the system/output maps so the uncontrollable and unobservable subspaces are simply the orthogonal complement to the Krylov subspace.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/krylov-subspace] Modern iterative methods such as Arnoldi iteration can be used for finding one (or a few) eigenvalues of large sparse matrices or solving large systems of linear equations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/krylov-subspace] They try to avoid matrix-matrix operations, but rather multiply vectors by the matrix and work with the resulting vectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/krylov-subspace] Starting with a vector b , one computes $Ab$ , then one multiplies that vector by A to find $A^{2}b$ and so on.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/krylov-subspace] All algorithms that work this way are referred to as Krylov subspace methods; they are among the most successful methods currently available in numerical linear algebra.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/krylov-subspace] These methods can be used in situations where there is an algorithm to compute the matrix-vector multiplication without there being an explicit representation of A , giving rise to matrix-free methods.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/krylov-subspace] Because the vectors usually soon become almost linearly dependent due to the properties of power iteration, methods relying on Krylov subspace frequently involve some orthogonalization scheme, such as Lanczos iteration for Hermitian matrices or Arnoldi iteration for more general matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/krylov-subspace] The best known Krylov subspace methods are the Conjugate gradient, IDR(s) (Induced dimension reduction), GMRES (generalized minimum residual), BiCGSTAB (biconjugate gradient stabilized), QMR (quasi minimal residual), TFQMR (transpose-free QMR) and MINRES (minimal residual method).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In numerical analysis and linear algebra, **lower–upper** (**LU**) **decomposition** or **factorization** factors a matrix as the product of a lower triangular matrix and an upper triangular matrix (see matrix multiplication and matrix decomposition).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The product sometimes includes a permutation matrix as well.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] LU decomposition can be viewed as the matrix form of Gaussian elimination.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Computers usually solve square systems of linear equations using LU decomposition, and it is also a key step when inverting a matrix or computing the determinant of a matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] It is also sometimes referred to as **LR** decomposition (factors into left and right triangular matrices).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The LU decomposition algorithm for general matrices was introduced by the Polish astronomer Tadeusz Banachiewicz in 1938.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] An **LU factorization** refers to expression of A into product of two factors – a lower triangular matrix L and an upper triangular matrix U such that *A* = *LU*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Sometimes factorization is impossible without prior reordering of A to prevent division by zero or uncontrolled growth of rounding errors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Hence alternative expression becomes *PAQ* = *LU*, where in formal notation permutation matrix factors P and Q indicate permutation of rows (or columns) of A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In theory P (or Q) is obtained by permutations of rows (or columns) of the identity matrix; in practice the corresponding permutations are applied directly to rows (or columns) of A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Matrix A of side n has $n^{2}$ coefficients while two triangle matrices combined contain *n*(*n* + 1) coefficients, and therefore n coefficients of matrices LU are not independent.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The convention is to set L unitriangular, i.e. with all n main diagonal elements equal to one.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] This demonstrates also, that operations on rows (e.g. pivoting) are equivalent to those on columns of a transposed matrix, and in general choice of row or column algorithm offers no advantage.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In the lower triangular matrix all elements above the main diagonal are zero, in the upper triangular matrix, all the elements below the diagonal are zero.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Without a proper ordering or permutations in the matrix, the factorization may fail to materialize.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] For example, it is easy to verify (by expanding the matrix multiplication) that ${\textstyle a_{11}=\ell _{11}u_{11}}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] If ${\textstyle a_{11}=0}$ , then at least one of ${\textstyle \ell _{11}}$ and ${\textstyle u_{11}}$ has to be zero, which implies that either L or U is singular.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] This is impossible if A is nonsingular (invertible).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In terms of operations, zeroing/elimination of remaining elements of first column of A involves division of ${\textstyle a_{21},a_{31}}$ with ${\textstyle a_{11}}$ , impossible if it is 0.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] It can be removed by simply reordering the rows of A so that the first element of the permuted matrix is nonzero.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The same problem in subsequent factorization steps can be removed the same way.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] For numerical stability against rounding errors/division by small numbers it is important to select ${\textstyle a_{11}}$ of large absolute value (cf. pivoting).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The above example of 3 × 3 matrices demonstrates that matrix product of top row and leftmost columns of involved matrices plays special role for LU to succeed.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Let us mark consecutive versions of matrices with $(0),\;(1),\dots$ and then let us write matrix product $A\equiv A^{(0)}=L^{(0)}U^{(0)}$ in such way that these rows and columns are separated from the rest.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Namely it turns out that one can multiply matrix blocks in such way as if they were ordinary numbers, i.e. row times column, except that now their components are sub-matrices, sometimes reduced to scalars or vectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Now comes the crucial observation: nothing prevents us to treat $A^{(1)}$ the same way as we did with $A^{(0)}$ , repeatedly.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] If dimension of A is n × n, after *n*− 1 such steps all columns ${\bf {v}}$ form sub-diagonal part of triangle matrix L and all pivots a combined with rows ${\bf {w}}^{\textsf {T}}$ form upper triangle matrix U , as required.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In the above example *n* = 3 so only two steps suffice.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The above procedure demonstrates that at no step the top diagonal pivot element a of consecutive sub-matrices can be zero.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] To avoid it columns or rows may be swapped so that a becomes nonzero.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Such procedure involving permutation is called *LUP*, decomposition with pivoting.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Permutation of columns corresponds to matrix product $AQ^{(0)}$ where $Q^{(0)}$ is a permutation matrix, i.e. the identity matrix I after the same column permutation.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] After all steps such LUP decomposition applies to $AQ^{(0)}\cdots Q^{(n-1)}\equiv AQ=LU$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Present computation scheme and similar in Cormen et al. are examples of **recurrence algorithms**.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] 2. final values of L and U matrices are obtained gradually, one row or column per step.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Recurrence algorithms are not overly costly in terms of algebraic operations yet they suffer from practical disadvantage due to need to update and store most elements of A at each step.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] It will be seen that by reordering calculations it is possible to dispose with storage of intermediate values.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] It turns out that a proper permutation of rows (or columns) to select column (or row) absolute maximal pivot *a*11 is sufficient for numerically stable LU factorization, except for known pathological cases.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] It is called ***LU factorization with partial pivoting*** (LUP): $PA=LU,\quad (AQ=LU),$ where L and U are again lower and upper triangular matrices, and P and Q are corresponding permutation matrices, which, when correspondingly left- and right-multiplied to A, reorder the rows and columns of A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] It turns out that all square matrices can be factorized in this form, and the factorization is numerically stable in practice.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] This makes LUP decomposition a useful technique in practice.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] A variant called ***rook pivoting*** at each step involves search of maximum element the way rook moves on a chessboard, along column, row, column again and so on till reaching a pivot maximal in both its row and column.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] It can be proven that for large matrices of random elements its cost of operations at each step is similarly to partial pivoting proportional to the length of matrix side unlike its square for full pivoting.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] An ***LU factorization with full pivoting*** involves both row and column permutations to find absolute maximum element in the whole submatrix: $PAQ=LU,$ where L, U, and P are defined as before, and Q is a permutation matrix that reorders the columns of A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] A ***lower-diagonal-upper decomposition*** (LDU) is a decomposition of the form $A=LDU,$ where D is a diagonal matrix, and L and U are unitriangular matrices, meaning that all the entries on the diagonals of L and U are one.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Above we required that A be a square matrix, but these decompositions can all be generalized to rectangular matrices as well.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In that case, L and D are square matrices both of which have the same number of rows as A, and U has exactly the same dimensions as A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] 'Upper triangular' should be interpreted as having only zero entries below the main diagonal, which starts at the upper left corner.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Similarly, the more precise term for U is that it is the row echelon form of the matrix A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] One way to find the LU decomposition of this simple matrix would be to simply solve the linear equations by inspection.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] This system of equations is underdetermined.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In this case any two nonzero elements of L and U matrices are parameters of the solution and can be set arbitrarily to any nonzero value.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Therefore, to find the unique LU decomposition, it is necessary to put some restriction on L and U matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] For example, we can conveniently require the lower triangular matrix L to be a unit triangular matrix, so that all the entries of its main diagonal are set to one.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Any square matrix A admits LUP and PLU factorizations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] If A is invertible, then it admits an LU (or LDU) factorization if and only if all its leading principal minors are nonzero (for example $\left[{\begin{smallmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{smallmatrix}}\right]$ does not admit an LU or LDU factorization).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] If A is a singular matrix of rank k, then it admits an LU factorization if the first k leading principal minors are nonzero, although the converse is not true.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] If a square, invertible matrix has an LDU factorization (with all diagonal entries of L and U equal to 1), then the factorization is unique.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In that case, the LU factorization is also unique if we require that the diagonal of either L or U consists of ones.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] 3. no LU factorization if the first (*n* − 1) columns are linearly independent and at least one leading principal minor is zero.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In Case 3, one can approximate an LU factorization by changing a diagonal entry aij to *aij* ± *ε* to avoid a zero leading principal minor.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] If A is a symmetric (or Hermitian, if A is complex) positive-definite matrix, we can arrange matters so that U is the conjugate transpose of L.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] This decomposition is called the Cholesky decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] If A is positive definite, then the Cholesky decomposition exists and is unique.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Furthermore, computing the Cholesky decomposition is more efficient and numerically more stable than computing some other LU decompositions.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] For a (not necessarily invertible) matrix over any field, the exact necessary and sufficient conditions under which it has an LU factorization are known.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The conditions are expressed in terms of the ranks of certain submatrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The Gaussian elimination algorithm for obtaining LU decomposition has also been extended to this most general case.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] When an LDU factorization exists and is unique, there is a closed (explicit) formula for the elements of L, D, and U in terms of ratios of determinants of certain submatrices of the original matrix A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In particular, *D*1 = *A*1,1, and for *i* = 2, ... , *n*, Di is the ratio of the i-th principal submatrix to the (*i* − 1)-th principal submatrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Computation of the determinants is computationally expensive, so this explicit formula is not used in practice.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The following algorithm is essentially a modified form of Gaussian elimination.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Computing an LU decomposition using this algorithm requires ⁠2/3⁠*n*3 floating-point operations, ignoring lower-order terms.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Partial pivoting adds only a quadratic term; this is not the case for full pivoting.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Given an N × N matrix $A=(a_{i,j})_{1\leq i,j\leq N}$ , define $A^{(0)}$ as the original, unmodified version of the matrix A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The parenthetical superscript (e.g., (0)) of the matrix A is the version of the matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The matrix *A*(*n*) is the A matrix in which the elements below the main diagonal have already been eliminated to 0 through Gaussian elimination for the first n columns.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] During this process, we gradually modify the matrix A using row operations until it becomes the matrix U in which all the elements below the main diagonal are equal to zero.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] During this, we will simultaneously create two separate matrices P and L, such that *PA* = *LU*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] We define the final permutation matrix P as the identity matrix which has all the same rows swapped in the same order as the A matrix while it transforms into the matrix U.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] For our matrix *A*(*n*−1), we may start by swapping rows to provide the desired conditions for the n-th column.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] For example, we might swap rows to perform partial pivoting, or we might do it to set the pivot element an,n on the main diagonal to a nonzero number so that we can complete the Gaussian elimination.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] For our matrix *A*(*n*−1), we want to set every element below $a_{n,n}^{(n-1)}$ to zero (where $a_{n,n}^{(n-1)}$ is the element in the n-th column of the main diagonal).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Once we have performed the row operations for the first *N* − 1 columns, we have obtained an upper triangular matrix *A*(*N*−1) which is denoted by U.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] We can also create the lower triangular matrix denoted as L, by directly inputting the previously calculated values of ℓi,n via the formula below.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Now these matrices have a relation such that *PA* = *LU*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Now let's compute the sequence of *L*1 ⋯ *L**N*−1.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] If there are two lower triangular matrices with 1s in the main diagonal, and neither have a nonzero item below the main diagonal in the same column as the other, then we can include all nonzero items at their same location in the product of the two matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Finally, multiply L1 together and generate the fused matrix denoted as L (as previously mentioned).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Using the matrix L, we obtain *A* = *LU*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] It is clear that in order for this algorithm to work, one needs to have $a_{n,n}^{(n-1)}\neq 0$ at each step (see the definition of ℓi,n.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] If this assumption fails at some point, one needs to interchange n-th row with another row below it before continuing.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] This is why an LU decomposition in general looks like *P*−1*A* = *LU*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The peculiar matrix notation used by Banachiewicz enabled him to multiply matrices column by column, a convenient feature for mechanical calculations as he could reveal consecutive factors by sliding a ruler to next rows of matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] For human readers however, his equations are best transformed into standard matrix notation.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] To obtain from a full matrix A triangle matrices U and L calculations, start by copying top row and leftmost column of A respectively into corresponding positions of matrices U and L.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The known unit diagonal elements of L are not stored nor used throughout the whole process.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Next calculations continue for the subsequent rows and columns till the bottom right corner of A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The figure illustrates calculations for 3rd row and column, assuming previous stages were already completed.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Involved matrices are named above squares marking their content.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Matrix products and subtractions are applied only to elements in the thick frame boxes.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Green filled thin frame boxes indicate values already known, from previous stages.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Blue boxes indicate places in U and L matrices for storing of results.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Note that at each stage the result elements of L need to be divided by the corresponding pivot element on the main diagonal of U.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] This applies to the leftmost column of L too.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Note that after completion of 3rd stage the involved elements of matrix A are no longer used and neither those from the previous stages.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] This enables replacement of these elements with the result values of U and L, i.e. execution of LU decomposition *in place*, so that the whole A is replaced with U and L except for the unit diagonal of L.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Banachiewicz LU algorithm is well suited for partial pivoting by choosing the absolute maximum pivot from the newly calculated row of U and subsequently swapping its columns so that it lands on the main diagonal.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] More details can be figured out from inspection of the enclosed Fortran90 code.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] All partial pivoting LU algorithms cost roughly the same amount, of order ${\textstyle O\left({2 \over 3}n^{3}\right)}$ operations, where n is the number of rows or columns of A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Note that the decomposition obtained through this procedure is a **Doolittle decomposition**: the main diagonal of L is composed solely of ones.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] If one would proceed by removing elements *above* the main diagonal by adding multiples of the *columns* (instead of removing elements *below* the diagonal by adding multiples of the *rows*), we would obtain a *Crout decomposition*, where the main diagonal of U is of ones.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Another (equivalent) way of producing a Crout decomposition of a given matrix A is to obtain a Doolittle decomposition of the transpose of A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Indeed, if *A*T = *L*0*U*0 is the LU-decomposition obtained through the algorithm presented in this section, then by taking *L* = *U*T 0 and *U* = *L*T 0, we have that *A* = *LU* is a Crout decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] It is possible to find a low rank approximation to an LU decomposition using a randomized algorithm.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] If two matrices of order n can be multiplied in time *M*(*n*), where *M*(*n*) ≥ *n**a* for some *a* > 2, then an LU-decomposition can be computed in time O(*M*(*n*)).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] This means, for example, that an O(*n*2.376) algorithm exists based on the Coppersmith–Winograd algorithm.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] See also for fast matrix multiplication algorithms article for more details.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Special algorithms have been developed for factorizing large sparse matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] These algorithms attempt to find sparse factors L and U.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Ideally, the cost of computation is determined by the number of nonzero entries, rather than by the size of the matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] These algorithms use the freedom to exchange rows and columns to minimize fill-in (entries that change from an initial zero to a nonzero value during the execution of an algorithm).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] General treatment of orderings that minimize fill-in can be addressed using graph theory.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] we want to solve the equation for **x**, given A and **b**.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Suppose we have already obtained the LUP decomposition of A such that *PA* = *LU*, so *LU***x** = *P***b**.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In both cases we are dealing with triangular matrices (L and U), which can be solved directly by forward and backward substitution without using the Gaussian elimination process (however we do need this process or equivalent to compute the LU decomposition itself).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The above procedure can be repeatedly applied to solve the equation multiple times for different **b**.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In this case it is faster (and more convenient) to do an LU decomposition of the matrix A once and then solve the triangular matrices for the different **b**, rather than using Gaussian elimination each time.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The matrices L and U could be thought to have "encoded" the Gaussian elimination process.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The cost of solving a system of linear equations is approximately ⁠2/3⁠*n*3 floating-point operations if the matrix A has size n.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] This makes it twice as fast as algorithms based on QR decomposition, which costs about ⁠4/3⁠*n*3 floating-point operations when Householder reflections are used.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] For this reason, LU decomposition is usually preferred.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] When solving systems of equations, **b** is usually treated as a vector with a length equal to the height of matrix A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] We can use the same algorithm presented earlier to solve for each column of matrix X.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Now suppose that B is the identity matrix of size n, In.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] It follows that the result X must be the inverse of A.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The second equation follows from the fact that the determinant of a triangular matrix is simply the product of its diagonal entries, and that the determinant of a permutation matrix is equal to (−1)*S* where S is the number of row exchanges in the decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] In the case of LU decomposition with full pivoting, det(*A*) also equals the right-hand side of the above equation, if we let S be the total number of row and column exchanges.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The same method readily applies to LU decomposition by setting P equal to the identity matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The LU decomposition is related to elimination of linear systems of equations, as e.g. described by Ralston.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The solution of N linear equations in N unknowns by elimination was already known to ancient Chinese.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Before Gauss many mathematicians in Eurasia were performing and perfecting it yet as the method became relegated to school grade, few of them left any detailed descriptions.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Thus the name Gaussian elimination is only a convenient abbreviation of a complex history.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] The Polish astronomer Tadeusz Banachiewicz introduced the LU decomposition in 1938.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Banachiewicz was the first to consider elimination in terms of matrices and in this way formulated LU decomposition, as demonstrated by his graphic illustration.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] His calculations follow ordinary matrix ones, yet notation deviates in that he preferred to write one factor transposed, to be able to multiply them mechanically column by column, by sliding ruler down consecutive rows of both (using arithmometer).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] where *IA* → *A*T; **x** ≡ [*x*1, ... , *xn*, −1]; *A*′ refers to A extended with the last column; and the last component of **x** is −1.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] Matrix formulae to calculate rows and columns of LU factors by recursion are given in the remaining part of Banachiewicz's paper as Eq.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] This paper by Banachiewicz contains both derivation of LU and *R*T*R* factors of respectively non-symmetric and symmetric matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/lu-decomposition] They are sometimes confused as later publications tend to tie his name solely with the rediscovery of Cholesky decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Numerical linear algebra aims to solve problems of continuous mathematics using finite precision computers, so its applications to the natural and social sciences are as vast as the applications of continuous mathematics.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] It is often a fundamental part of engineering and computational science problems, such as image and signal processing, telecommunication, computational finance, materials science simulations, structural biology, data mining, bioinformatics, fluid dynamics, and computational statistics.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Matrix methods are particularly used in finite difference methods, finite element methods, and the modeling of differential equations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Noting the broad applications of numerical linear algebra, Lloyd N.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Trefethen and David Bau, III argue that it is "as fundamental to the mathematical sciences as calculus and differential equations", even though it is a comparatively small field.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Because many properties of matrices and vectors also apply to functions and operators, numerical linear algebra can also be viewed as a type of functional analysis which has a particular emphasis on practical algorithms.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Numerical linear algebra's central concern with developing algorithms that do not introduce errors when applied to real data on a finite precision computer is often achieved by iterative methods rather than direct ones.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Numerical linear algebra was developed by computer pioneers like John von Neumann, Alan Turing, James H.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Wilkinson, Alston Scott Householder, George Forsythe, and Heinz Rutishauser, in order to apply the earliest computers to problems in continuous mathematics, such as ballistics problems and the solutions to systems of partial differential equations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The first serious attempt to minimize computer error in the application of algorithms to real data is John von Neumann and Herman Goldstine's work in 1947.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The field has grown as technology has increasingly enabled researchers to solve complex problems on extremely large high-precision matrices, and some numerical algorithms have grown in prominence as technologies like parallel computing have made them practical approaches to scientific problems.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] For many problems in applied linear algebra, it is useful to adopt the perspective of a matrix as being a concatenation of column vectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] For example, when solving the linear system $x=A^{-1}b$ , rather than understanding *x* as the product of $A^{-1}$ with *b*, it is helpful to think of *x* as the vector of coefficients in the linear expansion of *b* in the basis formed by the columns of *A*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Thinking of matrices as a concatenation of columns is also a practical approach for the purposes of matrix algorithms.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] This is because matrix algorithms frequently contain two nested loops: one over the columns of a matrix *A*, and another over the rows of *A*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The singular value decomposition of a matrix $A^{m\times n}$ is $A=U\Sigma V^{\ast }$ where *U* and *V* are unitary, and $\Sigma$ is diagonal.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The diagonal entries of $\Sigma$ are called the singular values of *A*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Because singular values are the square roots of the eigenvalues of $AA^{\ast }$ , there is a tight connection between the singular value decomposition and eigenvalue decompositions.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] This means that most methods for computing the singular value decomposition are similar to eigenvalue methods; perhaps the most common method involves Householder procedures.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The QR factorization of a matrix $A^{m\times n}$ is a matrix $Q^{m\times m}$ and a matrix $R^{m\times n}$ so that *A = QR*, where *Q* is orthogonal and *R* is upper triangular.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The two main algorithms for computing QR factorizations are the Gram–Schmidt process and the Householder transformation.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The QR factorization is often used to solve linear least-squares problems, and eigenvalue problems (by way of the iterative QR algorithm).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] An LU factorization of a matrix *A* consists of a lower triangular matrix *L* and an upper triangular matrix *U* so that *A = LU*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The matrix *U* is found by an upper triangularization procedure which involves left-multiplying *A* by a series of matrices $M_{1},\ldots ,M_{n-1}$ to form the product $M_{n-1}\cdots M_{1}A=U$ , so that equivalently $L=M_{1}^{-1}\cdots M_{n-1}^{-1}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The eigenvalue decomposition of a matrix $A^{m\times m}$ is $A=X\Lambda X^{-1}$ , where the columns of *X* are the eigenvectors of *A*, and $\Lambda$ is a diagonal matrix the diagonal entries of which are the corresponding eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] There is no direct method for finding the eigenvalue decomposition of an arbitrary matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Because it is not possible to write a program that finds the exact roots of an arbitrary polynomial in finite time, any general eigenvalue solver must necessarily be iterative.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Naive programs for Gaussian elimination are notoriously highly unstable, and produce huge errors when applied to matrices with many significant digits.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The simplest solution is to introduce pivoting, which produces a modified Gaussian elimination algorithm that is stable.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Numerical linear algebra characteristically approaches matrices as a concatenation of column vectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] In order to solve the linear system $x=A^{-1}b$ , the traditional algebraic approach is to understand *x* as the product of $A^{-1}$ with *b*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Numerical linear algebra instead interprets *x* as the vector of coefficients of the linear expansion of *b* in the basis formed by the columns of *A*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Many different decompositions can be used to solve the linear problem, depending on the characteristics of the matrix *A* and the vectors *x* and *b*, which may make one factorization much easier to obtain than others.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] If *A* = *QR* is a QR factorization of *A*, then equivalently $Rx=Q^{\ast }b$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] This is as easy to compute as a matrix factorization.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] This is closely related to the solution to the linear system using the singular value decomposition, because singular values of a matrix are the absolute values of its eigenvalues, which are also equivalent to the square roots of the absolute values of the eigenvalues of the Gram matrix $X^{*}X$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] And if *A* = *LU* is an *LU* factorization of *A*, then *Ax* = *b* can be solved using the triangular matrices *Ly* = *b* and *Ux* = *y*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Matrix decompositions suggest a number of ways to solve the linear system *r* = *b* − *Ax* where we seek to minimize *r*, as in the regression problem.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The QR algorithm solves this problem by computing the reduced QR factorization of *A* and rearranging to obtain ${\widehat {R}}x={\widehat {Q}}^{\ast }b$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] This upper triangular system can then be solved for *x*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The SVD also suggests an algorithm for obtaining linear least squares.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] By computing the reduced SVD decomposition $A={\widehat {U}}{\widehat {\Sigma }}V^{\ast }$ and then computing the vector ${\widehat {U}}^{\ast }b$ , we reduce the least squares problem to a simple diagonal system.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] The fact that least squares solutions can be produced by the QR and SVD factorizations means that, in addition to the classical normal equations method for solving least squares problems, these problems can also be solved by methods that include the Gram-Schmidt algorithm and Householder methods.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Allow that a problem is a function $f:X\to Y$ , where *X* is a normed vector space of data and *Y* is a normed vector space of solutions.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] For some data point $x\in X$ , the problem is said to be ill-conditioned if a small perturbation in *x* produces a large change in the value of *f*(*x*).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Instability is the tendency of computer algorithms, which depend on floating-point arithmetic, to produce results that differ dramatically from the exact mathematical solution to a problem.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] When a matrix contains real data with many significant digits, many algorithms for solving problems like linear systems of equation or least squares optimisation may produce highly inaccurate results.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Creating stable algorithms for ill-conditioned problems is a central concern in numerical linear algebra.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Some matrix decomposition methods may be unstable, but have straightforward modifications that make them stable; one example is the unstable Gram–Schmidt, which can easily be changed to produce the stable modified Gram–Schmidt.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Another classical problem in numerical linear algebra is the finding that Gaussian elimination is unstable, but becomes stable with the introduction of pivoting.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] There are two reasons that iterative algorithms are an important part of numerical linear algebra.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] First, many important numerical problems have no direct solution; in order to find the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of an arbitrary matrix, we can only adopt an iterative approach.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Second, noniterative algorithms for an arbitrary $m\times m$ matrix require $O(m^{3})$ time, which is a surprisingly high floor given that matrices contain only $m^{2}$ numbers.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Iterative approaches can take advantage of several features of some matrices to reduce this time.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] For example, when a matrix is sparse, an iterative algorithm can skip many of the steps that a direct approach would necessarily follow, even if they are redundant steps given a highly structured matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] When *A* is symmetric and we wish to solve the linear problem *Ax* = *b*, the classical iterative approach is the conjugate gradient method.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] If *A* is not symmetric, then examples of iterative solutions to the linear problem are the generalized minimal residual method and CGN.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] If *A* is symmetric, then to solve the eigenvalue and eigenvector problem we can use the Lanczos algorithm, and if *A* is non-symmetric, then we can use Arnoldi iteration.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Several programming languages use numerical linear algebra optimisation techniques and are designed to implement numerical linear algebra algorithms.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] These languages include MATLAB, Analytica, Maple, and Mathematica.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] Many numerical linear algebra commands in R rely on these more fundamental libraries like LAPACK.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/numerical-linear-algebra] More libraries can be found on the List of numerical libraries.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] The algorithm is also known as the **Von Mises iteration**.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Power iteration is a very simple algorithm, but it may converge slowly.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] The most time-consuming operation of the algorithm is the multiplication of matrix A by a vector, so it is effective for a very large sparse matrix with appropriate implementation.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] The speed of convergence is like $(\lambda _{2}/\lambda _{1})^{k}$ where k is the number of iterations, and $\lambda _{1}$ and $\lambda _{2}$ are, respectively, the eigenvalue of largest absolute value and an eigenvalue of second-largest absolute value (see a later section).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] In other words, convergence is exponential with base being the spectral gap.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] The power iteration algorithm starts with a vector $b_{0}$ , which may be an approximation to the dominant eigenvector or a random vector.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] So, at every iteration, the vector $b_{k}$ is multiplied by the matrix A and normalized.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] and the starting vector $b_{0}$ has a nonzero component in the direction of an eigenvector associated with the dominant eigenvalue, then a subsequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ converges to an eigenvector associated with the dominant eigenvalue.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Without the two assumptions above, the sequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ does not necessarily converge.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] where $v_{1}$ is an eigenvector associated with the dominant eigenvalue, and $\|r_{k}\|\rightarrow 0$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] The presence of the term $e^{i\phi _{k}}$ implies that $\left(b_{k}\right)$ does not converge unless $e^{i\phi _{k}}=1$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] converges to the dominant eigenvalue (with Rayleigh quotient).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] The vector $b_{k}$ converges to an associated eigenvector.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Ideally, one should use the Rayleigh quotient in order to get the associated eigenvalue.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] This algorithm is used to calculate the *Google PageRank*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Let A be decomposed into its Jordan canonical form: $A=VJV^{-1}$ , where the first column of V is an eigenvector of A corresponding to the dominant eigenvalue $\lambda _{1}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Since generically, the dominant eigenvalue of A is unique, the first Jordan block of J is the $1\times 1$ matrix $[\lambda _{1}],$ where $\lambda _{1}$ is the largest eigenvalue of A in magnitude.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] By assumption, $b_{0}$ has a nonzero component in the direction of the dominant eigenvector, so $c_{1}\neq 0$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] The sequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ is bounded, so it contains a convergent subsequence.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Note that the eigenvector corresponding to the dominant eigenvalue is only unique up to a scalar, so although the sequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ may not converge, $b_{k}$ is nearly an eigenvector of A for large k .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Suppose that $\lambda _{1}$ is the dominant eigenvalue, so that $|\lambda _{1}|>|\lambda _{j}|$ for all $j>1$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] If $b_{0}$ is chosen randomly (with uniform probability), then $c_{1}\neq 0$ with probability 1.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Therefore, $b_{k}$ converges to (a multiple of) the eigenvector $v_{1}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Thus, the method converges slowly if there is an eigenvalue close in magnitude to the dominant eigenvalue.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Although the power iteration method approximates only one eigenvalue of a matrix, it remains useful for certain computational problems.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] For instance, Google uses it to calculate the PageRank of documents in their search engine, and Twitter uses it to show users recommendations of whom to follow.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] The power iteration method is especially suitable for sparse matrices, such as the web matrix, or as the matrix-free method that does not require storing the coefficient matrix A explicitly, but can instead access a function evaluating matrix-vector products $Ax$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] For non-symmetric matrices that are well-conditioned the power iteration method can outperform more complex Arnoldi iteration.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] For symmetric matrices, the power iteration method is rarely used, since its convergence speed can be easily increased without sacrificing the small cost per iteration; see, e.g., Lanczos iteration and LOBPCG.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Some of the more advanced eigenvalue algorithms can be understood as variations of the power iteration.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] For instance, the inverse iteration method applies power iteration to the matrix $A^{-1}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Other algorithms look at the whole subspace generated by the vectors $b_{k}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] This subspace is known as the Krylov subspace.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] It can be computed by Arnoldi iteration or Lanczos iteration.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/power-iteration] Gram iteration is a super-linear and deterministic method to compute the largest eigenpair.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] In linear algebra, a **QR decomposition**, also known as a **QR factorization** or **QU factorization**, is a decomposition of a matrix *A* into a product *A* = *QR* of an orthonormal matrix *Q* and an upper triangular matrix *R*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] QR decomposition is often used to solve the linear least squares (LLS) problem and is the basis for a particular eigenvalue algorithm, the QR algorithm.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] where *Q* is an orthogonal matrix (its columns are orthogonal unit vectors meaning $Q^{\textsf {T}}=Q^{-1}$ ) and *R* is an upper triangular matrix (also called right triangular matrix).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] If *A* is invertible, then the factorization is unique if we require the diagonal elements of *R* to be positive.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] If instead *A* is a complex square matrix, then there is a decomposition *A* = *QR* where *Q* is a unitary matrix (so the conjugate transpose $Q^{\dagger }=Q^{-1}$ ).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] If *A* has *n* linearly independent columns, then the first *n* columns of *Q* form an orthonormal basis for the column space of *A*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] More generally, the first *k* columns of *Q* form an orthonormal basis for the span of the first *k* columns of *A* for any 1 ≤ *k* ≤ *n*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The fact that any column *k* of *A* only depends on the first *k* columns of *Q* corresponds to the triangular form of *R*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] More generally, we can factor a complex *m*×*n* matrix *A*, with *m* ≥ *n*, as the product of an *m*×*m* unitary matrix *Q* and an *m*×*n* upper triangular matrix *R*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Golub & Van Loan (1996, §5.2) call *Q*1*R*1 the *thin QR factorization* of *A*; Trefethen and Bau call this the *reduced QR factorization*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] If *A* is of full rank *n* and we require that the diagonal elements of *R*1 are positive then *R*1 and *Q*1 are unique, but in general *Q*2 is not.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] *R*1 is then equal to the upper triangular factor of the Cholesky decomposition of *A** *A* (= *A*T*A* if *A* is real).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Analogously, we can define QL, RQ, and LQ decompositions, with *L* being a *lower* triangular matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] There are several methods for actually computing the QR decomposition, such as the Gram–Schmidt process, Householder transformations, or Givens rotations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Each has a number of advantages and disadvantages.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Recall that an orthonormal matrix Q has the property $Q^{\textsf {T}}Q=I$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The RQ decomposition transforms a matrix *A* into the product of an upper triangular matrix *R* (also known as right-triangular) and an orthogonal matrix *Q*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The only difference from QR decomposition is the order of these matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] QR decomposition is Gram–Schmidt orthogonalization of columns of *A*, started from the first column.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] RQ decomposition is Gram–Schmidt orthogonalization of rows of *A*, started from the last row.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The Gram-Schmidt process is inherently numerically unstable.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] While the application of the projections has an appealing geometric analogy to orthogonalization, the orthogonalization itself is prone to numerical error.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] A significant advantage is the ease of implementation.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] A Householder reflection (or *Householder transformation*) is a transformation that takes a vector and reflects it about some plane or hyperplane.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] We can use this operation to calculate the *QR* factorization of an *m*-by-*n* matrix A with *m* ≥ *n*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Let $\mathbf {x}$ be an arbitrary real *m*-dimensional column vector of A such that $\|\mathbf {x} \|=|\alpha |$ for a scalar *α*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] *α* should get the same sign as the k -th coordinate of $\mathbf {x}$ , where $x_{k}$ is to be the pivot coordinate after which all entries are 0 in matrix *A*'s final upper triangular form.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] and substitute transposition by conjugate transposition in the construction of *Q* below.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] This can be used to gradually transform an *m*-by-*n* matrix *A* to upper triangular form.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] First, we multiply *A* with the Householder matrix *Q*1 we obtain when we choose the first matrix column for **x**.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] This results in a matrix *Q*1*A* with zeros in the left column (except for the first row).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] This can be repeated for *A*′ (obtained from *Q*1*A* by deleting the first row and first column), resulting in a Householder matrix *Q*′2.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] This method has greater numerical stability than the Gram–Schmidt method above.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The following table gives the number of operations in the *k*-th step of the QR-decomposition by the Householder transformation, assuming a square matrix with size *n*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] so we already have almost a triangular matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] after performing a direct sum with 1 to make sure the next step in the process works properly.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The matrix *Q* is orthogonal and *R* is upper triangular, so *A* = *QR* is the required QR decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The use of Householder transformations is inherently the most simple of the numerically stable QR decomposition algorithms due to the use of reflections as the mechanism for producing zeroes in the *R* matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] However, the Householder reflection algorithm is bandwidth heavy and difficult to parallelize, as every reflection that produces a new zero element changes the entirety of both *Q* and *R* matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The Householder QR method can be implemented in parallel with algorithms such as the TSQR algorithm (which stands for *Tall Skinny QR*).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] This algorithm can be applied in the case when the matrix *A* has *m >> n*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] This algorithm uses a binary reduction tree to compute local householder QR decomposition at each node in the forward pass, and re-constitute the Q matrix in the backward pass.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The binary tree structure aims at decreasing the amount of communication between processor to increase performance.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] QR decompositions can also be computed with a series of Givens rotations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Each rotation zeroes an element in the subdiagonal of the matrix, forming the *R* matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The concatenation of all the Givens rotations forms the orthogonal *Q* matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] In practice, Givens rotations are not actually performed by building a whole matrix and doing a matrix multiplication.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] A Givens rotation procedure is used instead which does the equivalent of the sparse Givens matrix multiplication, without the extra work of handling the sparse elements.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The Givens rotation procedure is useful in situations where only relatively few off-diagonal elements need to be zeroed, and is more easily parallelized than Householder transformations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] First, we need to form a rotation matrix that will zero the lowermost left element, $a_{31}=-4$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] We form this matrix using the Givens rotation method, and call the matrix $G_{1}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] We will first rotate the vector ${\begin{bmatrix}12&-4\end{bmatrix}}$ , to point along the *X* axis.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] And the result of $G_{1}A$ now has a zero in the $a_{31}$ element.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] We can similarly form Givens matrices $G_{2}$ and $G_{3}$ , which will zero the sub-diagonal elements $a_{21}$ and $a_{32}$ , forming a triangular matrix R .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The orthogonal matrix $Q^{\textsf {T}}$ is formed from the product of all the Givens matrices $Q^{\textsf {T}}=G_{3}G_{2}G_{1}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The QR decomposition via Givens rotations is the most involved to implement, as the ordering of the rows required to fully exploit the algorithm is not trivial to determine.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] However, it has a significant advantage in that each new zero element $a_{ij}$ affects only the row with the element to be zeroed (*i*) and a row above (*j*).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] This makes the Givens rotation algorithm more bandwidth efficient and parallelizable than the Householder reflection technique.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] It is possible to compute the QR decomposition in a fast way with the use of fast matrix multiplication algorithms in the time $O({n^{\omega }})$ for $~2.37\leq \omega <3$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] We can use QR decomposition to find the determinant of a square matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Suppose a matrix is decomposed as $A=QR$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] where the $r_{ii}$ are the entries on the diagonal of R .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] where the $\lambda _{i}$ are eigenvalues of A .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] We can extend the above properties to a non-square complex matrix A by introducing the definition of QR decomposition for non-square complex matrices and replacing eigenvalues with singular values.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] where 0 denotes the zero matrix and Q is a unitary matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] where the $\sigma _{i}$ are the singular values of A .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Note that the singular values of A and R are identical, although their complex eigenvalues may be different.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] It follows that the QR decomposition can be used to efficiently calculate the product of the eigenvalues or singular values of a matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Column pivoting is useful when *A* is (nearly) rank deficient, or is suspected of being so.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] *P* is usually chosen so that the diagonal elements of *R* are non-increasing: $\left|r_{11}\right|\geq \left|r_{22}\right|\geq \cdots \geq \left|r_{nn}\right|$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] This can be used to find the (numerical) rank of *A* at lower computational cost than a singular value decomposition, forming the basis of so-called rank-revealing QR algorithms.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Compared to the direct matrix inverse, inverse solutions using QR decomposition are more numerically stable as evidenced by their reduced condition numbers.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Here $R_{1}$ is a square $m\times m$ right triangular matrix, and the zero matrix has dimension $(n-m)\times m$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The latter technique enjoys greater numerical accuracy and lower computations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] To find a solution ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}$ to the overdetermined ( $m\geq n$ ) problem $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ which minimizes the norm $\left\|A{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}-\mathbf {b} \right\|$ , first find the QR factorization of A : $A=QR$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] The solution can then be expressed as ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}=R_{1}^{-1}\left(Q_{1}^{\textsf {T}}\mathbf {b} \right)$ , where $Q_{1}$ is an $m\times n$ matrix containing the first n columns of the full orthonormal basis Q and where $R_{1}$ is as before.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Equivalent to the underdetermined case, back substitution can be used to quickly and accurately find this ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}$ without explicitly inverting $R_{1}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/qr-decomposition] Iwasawa decomposition generalizes QR decomposition to semi-simple Lie groups.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In linear algebra, the **singular value decomposition** (**SVD**) is a factorization of a real or complex matrix into a rotation, followed by a scaling, followed by another rotation.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It generalizes the eigendecomposition of a square normal matrix with an orthonormal eigenbasis to any ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is related to the polar decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Such decompositions always exist for any complex matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is real, then ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ can be guaranteed to be real orthogonal matrices; in such contexts, the SVD is often denoted ⁠ $\mathbf {U\Sigma V} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The diagonal entries $\sigma _{i}=\mathbf {\Sigma } _{ii}$ of $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ are uniquely determined by ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ up to reordering and are known as the singular values of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The number of non-zero singular values is equal to the rank of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and the columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ are called left-singular vectors and right-singular vectors of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠, respectively.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] However, it is always possible to choose the decomposition such that the singular values $\mathbf {\Sigma } _{ii}$ are in descending order.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In this case, $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ (but not ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠) is uniquely determined by ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Mathematical applications of the SVD include computing the pseudoinverse, matrix approximation, and determining the rank, range, and null space of a matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD is also extremely useful in many areas of science, engineering, and statistics, such as signal processing, least squares fitting of data, and process control.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In the special case when ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is an ⁠ $m\times m$ ⁠ real square matrix, the matrices ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ can be chosen to be real ⁠ $m\times m$ ⁠ matrices too.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In that case, "unitary" is the same as "orthogonal".
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In particular, if ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ has a positive determinant, then ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ can be chosen to be both rotations with reflections, or both rotations without reflections.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If the determinant is negative, exactly one of them will have a reflection.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If the determinant is zero, each can be independently chosen to be of either type.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If the matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is real but not square, namely ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ with ⁠ $m\neq n$ ⁠, it can be interpreted as a linear transformation from ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠ to ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As shown in the figure, the singular values can be interpreted as the magnitude of the semiaxes of an ellipse in 2D.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This concept can be generalized to ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional Euclidean space, with the singular values of any ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ square matrix being viewed as the magnitude of the semiaxis of an ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional ellipsoid.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Similarly, the singular values of any ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ matrix can be viewed as the magnitude of the semiaxis of an ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional ellipsoid in ⁠ m ⁠-dimensional space, for example as an ellipse in a (tilted) 2D plane in a 3D space.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Singular values encode magnitude of the semiaxis, while singular vectors encode direction.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Since ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ are unitary, the columns of each of them form a set of orthonormal vectors, which can be regarded as basis vectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ maps the basis vector ⁠ $\mathbf {V} _{i}$ ⁠ to the stretched unit vector ⁠ $\sigma _{i}\mathbf {U} _{i}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] By the definition of a unitary matrix, the same is true for their conjugate transposes ⁠ $\mathbf {U} ^{*}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠, except the geometric interpretation of the singular values as stretches is lost.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] When ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is a positive-semidefinite Hermitian matrix, ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ are both equal to the unitary matrix used to diagonalize ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] However, when ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is not positive-semidefinite and Hermitian but still diagonalizable, its eigendecomposition and singular value decomposition are distinct.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] With respect to these bases, the map ⁠ T ⁠ is therefore represented by a diagonal matrix with non-negative real diagonal entries.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] To get a more visual flavor of singular values and SVD factorization – at least when working on real vector spaces – consider the sphere ⁠ S ⁠ of radius one in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The linear map ⁠ T ⁠ maps this sphere onto an ellipsoid in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Non-zero singular values are simply the lengths of the semi-axes of this ellipsoid.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] These directions happen to be mutually orthogonal.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Apply first an isometry ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ sending these directions to the coordinate axes of ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] On a second move, apply an endomorphism ⁠ $\mathbf {D}$ ⁠ diagonalized along the coordinate axes and stretching or shrinking in each direction, using the semi-axis lengths of ⁠ $T(S)$ ⁠ as scaling coefficients.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The composition ⁠ $\mathbf {D} \circ \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ then sends the unit-sphere onto an ellipsoid isometric to ⁠ $T(S)$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] To define the third and last move, apply an isometry ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ to this ellipsoid to obtain ⁠ $T(S)$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As can be easily checked, the composition ⁠ $\mathbf {U} \circ \mathbf {D} \circ \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ coincides with ⁠ T ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The singular values of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ are the diagonal entries of ⁠ $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ ⁠: ${\color {PineGreen}3},{\color {BrickRed}{\sqrt {5}}},{\color {BlueViolet}2},{\color {CadetBlue}0}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The corresponding left- and right-singular vectors are the columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and rows of ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠, respectively.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ has rank ⁠ 3 ⁠, so there are only three non-zero singular values.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Likewise for the last column of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The vectors ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠ are called **left-singular** and **right-singular vectors** for ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠, respectively.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In any singular value decomposition $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {U} \mathbf {\Sigma } \mathbf {V} ^{*},$ the diagonal entries of ⁠ $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ ⁠ are equal to the singular values of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The first ⁠ $p=\min\{m,n\}$ ⁠ columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ are, respectively, left- and right-singular vectors for the corresponding singular values.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A singular value for which we can find two left- (or right-) singular vectors that are linearly independent is called *degenerate*.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] If ⁠ $\mathbf {u} _{1}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {u} _{2}$ ⁠ are two left-singular vectors which both correspond to the singular value ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠, then any normalized linear combination of the two vectors is also a left-singular vector corresponding to the singular value ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The similar statement is true for right-singular vectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The numbers of independent left- and right-singular vectors coincide, and these singular vectors appear in the same columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠: those corresponding to the diagonal elements of ⁠ $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ ⁠ with the same value ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As an exception, the left- and right-singular vectors of singular value ⁠ 0 ⁠ comprise all unit vectors in the cokernel and kernel, respectively, of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] By the rank–nullity theorem, these subspaces cannot have the same dimension if ⁠ $m\neq n$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Even when all singular values are non-zero, if ⁠ $m>n$ ⁠, then the cokernel is non-trivial, in which case ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ is padded with ⁠ $m-n$ ⁠ orthogonal [orthonormal?] vectors from the cokernel.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Conversely, if ⁠ $m<n$ ⁠, then ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ is padded by ⁠ $n-m$ ⁠ orthogonal [orthonormal?] vectors from the kernel.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] However, if the singular value ⁠ 0 ⁠ exists, the extra columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ already appear as left- or right-singular vectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Non-degenerate singular values always have unique left- and right-singular vectors, up to multiplication by a (unit) phase factor ⁠ $e^{i\varphi }$ ⁠ (for the real case, up to a sign).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In general, the SVD is unique up to arbitrary unitary transformations applied uniformly to the column vectors of both ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The singular value decomposition is very general in the sense that it can be applied to any ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ matrix, whereas eigenvalue decomposition can only be applied to square diagonalizable matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Nevertheless, the two decompositions are related.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The right-hand sides of these relations describe the eigenvalue decompositions of the left-hand sides.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] When ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is positive semi-definite, ⁠ $\sigma _{i}$ ⁠ will be non-negative real numbers so that the decomposition ⁠ $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {U} \mathbf {D} \mathbf {U} ^{*}$ ⁠ is also a singular value decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The singular value decomposition can be used for computing the pseudoinverse of a matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The pseudoinverse is one way to solve linear least squares problems.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A set of homogeneous linear equations can be written as ⁠ $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x} =\mathbf {0}$ ⁠ for a matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠, vector ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠, and zero vector ⁠ $\mathbf {0}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A typical situation is that ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠ is known and a non-zero ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠ is to be determined which satisfies the equation.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Such an ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠ belongs to ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠'s null space and is sometimes called a (right) null vector of ⁠ $\mathbf {A} .$ ⁠ The vector ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠ can be characterized as a right-singular vector corresponding to a singular value of ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠ that is zero.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This observation means that if ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠ is a square matrix and has no vanishing singular value, the equation has no non-zero ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠ as a solution.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It also means that if there are several vanishing singular values, any linear combination of the corresponding right-singular vectors is a valid solution.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A total least squares problem seeks the vector ⁠ $\mathbf {x}$ ⁠ that minimizes the 2-norm of a vector ⁠ $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x}$ ⁠ under the constraint $\|\mathbf {x} \|=1.$ The solution turns out to be the right-singular vector of ⁠ $\mathbf {A}$ ⁠ corresponding to the smallest singular value.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] As a consequence, the rank of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ equals the number of non-zero singular values which is the same as the number of non-zero diagonal elements in $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In numerical linear algebra the singular values can be used to determine the *effective rank* of a matrix, as rounding error may lead to small but non-zero singular values in a rank deficient matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Singular values beyond a significant gap are assumed to be numerically equivalent to zero.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Some practical applications need to solve the problem of approximating a matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ with another matrix ${\tilde {\mathbf {M} }}$ , said to be truncated, which has a specific rank ⁠ r ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This is known as the **Eckart–Young theorem**, as it was proved by those two authors in 1936.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] One practical consequence of the low-rank approximation given by SVD is that a greyscale image represented as an $m\times n$ matrix $\mathbf {A}$ , can be efficiently represented by keeping the first k singular values and corresponding vectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] $\mathbf {A} _{k}=\sum _{j=1}^{k}\sigma _{j}\mathbf {u} _{j}\mathbf {v} _{j}^{T}$ gives an image with the best 2-norm error out of all rank k approximations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Thus, the task becomes finding an approximation that balances retaining perceptual fidelity with the number of vectors required to reconstruct the image.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Storing $\mathbf {A} _{k}$ requires only $k(n+m+1)$ floating-point numbers compared to $nm$ integers.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This same idea extends to color images by applying this operation to each channel or stacking the channels into one matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Since the singular values of most natural images decay quickly, most of their variance is often captured by a small k .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] For a 1528 × 1225 greyscale image, we can achieve a relative error of $.7\%$ with as little as $k=100$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In practice, however, computing the SVD can be too computationally expensive and the resulting compression is typically less storage efficient than a specialized algorithm such as JPEG.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD can be thought of as decomposing a matrix into a weighted, ordered sum of separable matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Here ⁠ $\mathbf {U} _{i}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V} _{i}$ ⁠ are the ⁠ i ⁠-th columns of the corresponding SVD matrices, ⁠ $\sigma _{i}$ ⁠ are the ordered singular values, and each ⁠ $\mathbf {A} _{i}$ ⁠ is separable.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD can be used to find the decomposition of an image processing filter into separable horizontal and vertical filters.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Note that the number of non-zero ⁠ $\sigma _{i}$ ⁠ is exactly the rank of the matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Separable models often arise in biological systems, and the SVD factorization is useful to analyze such systems.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] For example, some visual area V1 simple cells' receptive fields can be well described by a Gabor filter in the space domain multiplied by a modulation function in the time domain.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Thus, given a linear filter evaluated through, for example, reverse correlation, one can rearrange the two spatial dimensions into one dimension, thus yielding a two-dimensional filter (space, time) which can be decomposed through SVD.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The first column of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ in the SVD factorization is then a Gabor while the first column of ⁠ $\mathbf {V}$ ⁠ represents the time modulation (or vice versa).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] which is the fraction of the power in the matrix M which is accounted for by the first separable matrix in the decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Equivalently, the solution is the unitary matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {R} =\mathbf {U} \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ of the Polar Decomposition $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {R} \mathbf {P} =\mathbf {P} '\mathbf {R}$ in either order of stretch and rotation, as described above.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This problem is equivalent to finding the nearest orthogonal matrix to a given matrix $\mathbf {M} =\mathbf {A} ^{\operatorname {T} }\mathbf {B}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The Kabsch algorithm (called Wahba's problem in other fields) uses SVD to compute the optimal rotation (with respect to least-squares minimization) that will align a set of points with a corresponding set of points.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is used, among other applications, to compare the structures of molecules.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Let $\mathbf {X} \in \mathbb {R} ^{N\times p}$ be a data matrix where each of the N rows is a (feature-wise) mean-centered observation, each of dimension p .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] We see that $\mathbf {V} {\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}$ contains the scores of the rows of $\mathbf {X}$ (i.e. each observation), and $\mathbf {U}$ is the matrix whose columns are principal component loading vectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD and pseudoinverse have been successfully applied to signal processing, image processing and big data (e.g., in genomic signal processing).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD is also applied extensively to the study of linear inverse problems and is useful in the analysis of regularization methods such as that of Tikhonov.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is widely used in statistics, where it is related to principal component analysis and to correspondence analysis, and in signal processing and pattern recognition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It is also used in output-only modal analysis, where the non-scaled mode shapes can be determined from the singular vectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Yet another usage is latent semantic indexing in natural-language text processing.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In general numerical computation involving linear or linearized systems, there is a universal constant that characterizes the regularity or singularity of a problem, which is the system's "condition number" $\kappa :=\sigma _{\text{max}}/\sigma _{\text{min}}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] It often controls the error rate or convergence rate of a given computational scheme on such systems.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD also plays a crucial role in the field of quantum information, in a form often referred to as the Schmidt decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Through it, states of two quantum systems are naturally decomposed, providing a necessary and sufficient condition for them to be entangled: if the rank of the $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ matrix is larger than one.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The output singular vectors in this case are entire weather systems.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] These perturbations are then run through the full nonlinear model to generate an ensemble forecast, giving a handle on some of the uncertainty that should be allowed for around the current central prediction.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] SVD has also been applied to reduced order modelling.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The aim of reduced order modelling is to reduce the number of degrees of freedom in a complex system which is to be modeled.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] SVD was coupled with radial basis functions to interpolate solutions to three-dimensional unsteady flow problems.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Interestingly, SVD has been used to improve gravitational waveform modeling by the ground-based gravitational-wave interferometer aLIGO.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] SVD can help to increase the accuracy and speed of waveform generation to support gravitational-waves searches and update two different waveform models.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Singular value decomposition is used in recommender systems to predict people's item ratings.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Distributed algorithms have been developed for the purpose of calculating the SVD on clusters of commodity machines.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] Low-rank SVD has been applied for hotspot detection from spatiotemporal data with application to disease outbreak detection.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] A combination of SVD and higher-order SVD also has been applied for real time event detection from complex data streams (multivariate data with space and time dimensions) in disease surveillance.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] In astrodynamics, the SVD and its variants are used as an option to determine suitable maneuver directions for transfer trajectory design and orbital station-keeping.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] The SVD can be used to measure the similarity between real-valued matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] By measuring the angles between the singular vectors, the inherent two-dimensional structure of matrices is accounted for.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p01] This method was shown to outperform cosine similarity and Frobenius norm in most cases, including brain activity measurements from neuroscience experiments.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] An eigenvalue ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ of a matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is characterized by the algebraic relation ⁠ $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {u} =\lambda \mathbf {u} .$ ⁠ When ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is Hermitian, a variational characterization is also available.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Let ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ be a real ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ symmetric matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The complex Hermitian case is similar; there ⁠ $f(\mathbf {x} )=\mathbf {x} ^{*}\mathbf {M} \mathbf {x}$ ⁠ is a real-valued function of ⁠ $2n$ ⁠ real variables.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Singular values are similar in that they can be described algebraically or from variational principles.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Although, unlike the eigenvalue case, Hermiticity, or symmetry, of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is no longer required.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This section gives these two arguments for existence of singular value decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Let $\mathbf {M}$ be an ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ complex matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Note that $\mathbf {V}$ is here by definition a matrix whose i -th column is the i -th eigenvector of $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ , corresponding to the eigenvalue ${\bar {\mathbf {D} }}_{ii}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Moreover, the j -th column of $\mathbf {V}$ , for $j>\ell$ , is an eigenvector of $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ with eigenvalue ${\bar {\mathbf {D} }}_{jj}=0$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Moreover, the second equation implies $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {V} _{2}=\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] since $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {V} _{2}=\mathbf {0} .$ This can be also seen as immediate consequence of the fact that $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {V} _{1}\mathbf {V} _{1}^{*}=\mathbf {M}$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] We see that this is almost the desired result, except that $\mathbf {U} _{1}$ and $\mathbf {V} _{1}$ are in general not unitary, since they might not be square.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, we do know that the number of rows of $\mathbf {U} _{1}$ is no smaller than the number of columns, since the dimensions of $\mathbf {D}$ is no greater than m and n .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This means that we can choose $\mathbf {U} _{2}$ such that $\mathbf {U} ={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {U} _{1}&\mathbf {U} _{2}\end{bmatrix}}$ is unitary.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] For ⁠ $\mathbf {V} _{1}$ ⁠ we already have ⁠ $\mathbf {V} _{2}$ ⁠ to make it unitary.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] where extra zero rows are added **or removed** to make the number of zero rows equal the number of columns of ⁠ $\mathbf {U} _{2},$ ⁠ and hence the overall dimensions of $\mathbf {\Sigma }$ equal to $m\times n$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Notice the argument could begin with diagonalizing ⁠ $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {M} ^{*}$ ⁠ rather than ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ (This shows directly that ⁠ $\mathbf {M} \mathbf {M} ^{*}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ have the same non-zero eigenvalues).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular values can also be characterized as the maxima of ⁠ $\mathbf {u} ^{\mathrm {T} }\mathbf {M} \mathbf {v} ,$ ⁠ considered as a function of ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v} ,$ ⁠ over particular subspaces.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular vectors are the values of ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠ where these maxima are attained.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Let ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ denote an ⁠ $m\times n$ ⁠ matrix with real entries.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Consider the function ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠ restricted to ⁠ $S^{m-1}\times S^{n-1}.$ ⁠ Since both ⁠ $S^{m-1}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $S^{n-1}$ ⁠ are compact sets, their product is also compact.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If it were negative, changing the sign of either ⁠ $\mathbf {u} _{1}$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\mathbf {v} _{1}$ ⁠ would make it positive and therefore larger.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] More singular vectors and singular values can be found by maximizing ⁠ $\sigma (\mathbf {u} ,\mathbf {v} )$ ⁠ over normalized ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠ which are orthogonal to ⁠ $\mathbf {u} _{1}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v} _{1},$ ⁠ respectively.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The passage from real to complex is similar to the eigenvalue case.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] One-sided Jacobi algorithm is an iterative algorithm, where a matrix is iteratively transformed into a matrix with orthogonal columns.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The elementary iteration is given as a Jacobi rotation, $M\leftarrow MJ(p,q,\theta ),$ where the angle $\theta$ of the Jacobi rotation matrix $J(p,q,\theta )$ is chosen such that after the rotation the columns with numbers p and q become orthogonal.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The indices $(p,q)$ are swept cyclically, $(p=1\dots m,q=p+1\dots m)$ , where m is the number of columns.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Two-sided Jacobi SVD algorithm—a generalization of the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm—is an iterative algorithm where a square matrix is iteratively transformed into a diagonal matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If the matrix is not square the QR decomposition is performed first and then the algorithm is applied to the R matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The iterations proceeds exactly as in the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm: by cyclic sweeps over all off-diagonal elements.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] After the algorithm has converged the resulting diagonal matrix contains the singular values.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The SVD of a matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ is typically computed by a two-step procedure.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In the first step, the matrix is reduced to a bidiagonal matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This takes order ⁠ $O(mn^{2})$ ⁠ floating-point operations (*flop*), assuming that ⁠ $m\geq n.$ ⁠ The second step is to compute the SVD of the bidiagonal matrix.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This step can only be done with an iterative method (as with eigenvalue algorithms).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, in practice it suffices to compute the SVD up to a certain precision, like the machine epsilon.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If this precision is considered constant, then the second step takes ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ iterations, each costing ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ flops.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Thus, the first step is more expensive, and the overall cost is ⁠ $O(mn^{2})$ ⁠ flops.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The first step can be done using Householder reflections for a cost of ⁠ $4mn^{2}-4n^{3}/3$ ⁠ flops, assuming that only the singular values are needed and not the singular vectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If ⁠ m ⁠ is much larger than ⁠ n ⁠ then it is advantageous to first reduce the matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ to a triangular matrix with the QR decomposition and then use Householder reflections to further reduce the matrix to bidiagonal form; the combined cost is ⁠ $2mn^{2}+2n^{3}$ ⁠ flops.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The second step can be done by a variant of the QR algorithm for the computation of eigenvalues, which was first described by Golub and Kahan in 1965.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The LAPACK subroutine `DBDSQR` implements this iterative method, with some modifications to cover the case where the singular values are very small.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Together with a first step using Householder reflections and, if appropriate, QR decomposition, this forms the `DGESVD` routine for the computation of the singular value decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The same algorithm is implemented in the GNU Scientific Library (GSL).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The GSL also offers an alternative method that uses a one-sided Jacobi orthogonalization in step 2.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This method computes the SVD of the bidiagonal matrix by solving a sequence of ⁠ $2\times 2$ ⁠ SVD problems, similar to how the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm solves a sequence of ⁠ $2\times 2$ ⁠ eigenvalue methods.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Yet another method for step 2 uses the idea of divide-and-conquer eigenvalue algorithms.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] There is an alternative way that does not explicitly use the eigenvalue decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The approaches that use eigenvalue decompositions are based on the QR algorithm, which is well-developed to be stable and fast.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Note that the singular values are real and right- and left- singular vectors are not required to form similarity transformations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] One can iteratively alternate between the QR decomposition and the LQ decomposition to find the real diagonal Hermitian matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Eventually, this iteration between QR decomposition and LQ decomposition produces left- and right- unitary singular matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This approach cannot readily be accelerated, as the QR algorithm can with spectral shifts or deflation.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This is because the shift method is not easily defined without using similarity transformations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, this iterative approach is very simple to implement, so is a good choice when speed does not matter.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This method also provides insight into how purely orthogonal/unitary transformations can obtain the SVD.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The methods above yield ⁠ $O(mn^{2})$ ⁠ algorithms for the SVD of an $m\times n$ matrix M where $m\geq n$ .
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Demmel, Dumitriu and Holtz show that for a symmetric M (i.e. $m=n$ ) the SVD can normwise stably be computed in $O(n^{\omega +\eta })$ arithmetic operations where $\omega$ is the matrix multiplication exponent and $\eta >0$ is any constant, i.e. essentially in matrix multiplication time.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular values of a ⁠ $2\times 2$ ⁠ matrix can be found analytically.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] where $z_{i}\in \mathbb {C}$ are complex numbers that parameterize the matrix, ⁠ $\mathbf {I}$ ⁠ is the identity matrix, and $\sigma _{i}$ denote the Pauli matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In applications it is quite unusual for the full SVD, including a full unitary decomposition of the null-space of the matrix, to be required.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Instead, it is often sufficient (as well as faster, and more economical for storage) to compute a reduced version of the SVD.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The thin SVD uses significantly less space and computation time if ⁠ $k\ll \max(m,n).$ ⁠ The first stage in its calculation will usually be a QR decomposition of ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ,$ ⁠ which can make for a significantly quicker calculation in this case.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Only the ⁠ r ⁠ column vectors of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ r ⁠ row vectors of ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ corresponding to the non-zero singular values ⁠ $\mathbf {\Sigma } _{r}$ ⁠ are calculated.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The remaining vectors of ⁠ $\mathbf {U}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ are not calculated.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In many applications the number ⁠ r ⁠ of the non-zero singular values is large making even the Compact SVD impractical to compute.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In such cases, the smallest singular values may need to be truncated to compute only ⁠ $t\ll r$ ⁠ non-zero singular values.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This can be much quicker and more economical than the compact SVD if ⁠ $t\ll r,$ ⁠ but requires a completely different toolset of numerical solvers.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In applications that require an approximation to the Moore–Penrose inverse of the matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ,$ ⁠ the smallest singular values of ⁠ $\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ are of interest, which are more challenging to compute compared to the largest ones.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Truncated SVD is employed in latent semantic indexing.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] For this reason, it is also called the operator 2-norm.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] One can easily verify the relationship between the Ky Fan 1-norm and singular values.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The last of the Ky Fan norms, the sum of all singular values, is the trace norm (also known as the 'nuclear norm'), defined by $\|\mathbf {M} \|=\operatorname {Tr} (\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M} )^{1/2}$ (the eigenvalues of ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M}$ ⁠ are the squares of the singular values).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular values are related to another norm on the space of operators.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In addition, the Frobenius norm and the trace norm (the nuclear norm) are special cases of the Schatten norm.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This can be shown by mimicking the linear algebraic argument for the matrix case above. ⁠ $\mathbf {V} T_{f}\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ is the unique positive square root of ⁠ $\mathbf {M} ^{*}\mathbf {M} ,$ ⁠ as given by the Borel functional calculus for self-adjoint operators.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] and notice that ⁠ $\mathbf {U} \mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ is still a partial isometry while ⁠ $\mathbf {V} T_{f}\mathbf {V} ^{*}$ ⁠ is positive.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The notion of singular values and left/right-singular vectors can be extended to compact operator on Hilbert space as they have a discrete spectrum.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] If ⁠ T ⁠ is compact, every non-zero ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ in its spectrum is an eigenvalue.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Furthermore, a compact self-adjoint operator can be diagonalized by its eigenvectors.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Applying the diagonalization result, the unitary image of its positive square root ⁠ $T_{f}$ ⁠ has a set of orthonormal eigenvectors ⁠ $\{e_{i}\}$ ⁠ corresponding to strictly positive eigenvalues ⁠ $\{\sigma _{i}\}$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Compact operators on a Hilbert space are the closure of finite-rank operators in the uniform operator topology.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The above series expression gives an explicit such representation.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The singular value decomposition was originally developed by differential geometers, who wished to determine whether a real bilinear form could be made equal to another by independent orthogonal transformations of the two spaces it acts on.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Eugenio Beltrami and Camille Jordan discovered independently, in 1873 and 1874 respectively, that the singular values of the bilinear forms, represented as a matrix, form a complete set of invariants for bilinear forms under orthogonal substitutions.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] James Joseph Sylvester also arrived at the singular value decomposition for real square matrices in 1889, apparently independently of both Beltrami and Jordan.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Sylvester called the singular values the *canonical multipliers* of the matrix ⁠ $\mathbf {A} .$ ⁠ The fourth mathematician to discover the singular value decomposition independently is Autonne in 1915, who arrived at it via the polar decomposition.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] The first proof of the singular value decomposition for rectangular and complex matrices seems to be by Carl Eckart and Gale J.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Young in 1936; they saw it as a generalization of the principal axis transformation for Hermitian matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In 1907, Erhard Schmidt defined an analog of singular values for integral operators (which are compact, under some weak technical assumptions); it seems he was unaware of the parallel work on singular values of finite matrices.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] This theory was further developed by Émile Picard in 1910, who is the first to call the numbers $\sigma _{k}$ *singular values* (or in French, *valeurs singulières*).
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] Practical methods for computing the SVD date back to Kogbetliantz in 1954–1955 and Hestenes in 1958, resembling closely the Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm, which uses plane rotations or Givens rotations.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] However, these were replaced by the method of Gene Golub and William Kahan published in 1965, which uses Householder transformations or reflections.
[src:numerical-linear-algebra/singular-value-decomposition-p02] In 1970, Golub and Christian Reinsch published a variant of the Golub/Kahan algorithm that is still the one most-used today.
